First, I wanted to see if the [sh] process was a service or not so I tried the following command <sudo systemctl -p NAME | grep sh. This command greps the two letters sh from the name of any running service. Basically, it searches for any service with the name sh or contains sh. 
I got zero services. So tried a different version this time <sudo systemctl --type=service | grep sh> and got nothing. Only then I realized that the only process that I'm able to grep is systemd-resolve. And I got the full name: systemd-resolved.service. {{{
{ you can try all these commands on your own Linux if you find my explanation confusing or if you want to follow along}}}}}}}
I still didn't think that was the malicious service I needed to disable so I moved on to trying the ps command. 
Comptia question does say {{ adversary has achieved persistence by creating a *******systemd service******}} but you never trust Fu**** Comptia. So I wanted to try more commands just to make sure I was right.
